(130, 'http://blogbaladi.com/the-mansion-beirut/', 'The Mansion – Beirut', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_220521-425x318.jpg', 'After I posted about the Speed Dating event, and heard that they serve Pork Ribs at their 30$ Open Wine BBQ, I decided t...', 'blogbaladi', 1362472200, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_220521-425x318.jpg" alt="20130223_220521" width="425" height="318"></p>\n<p>After I posted about <a href="http://blogbaladi.com/speed-dating-at-the-mansion/">the Speed Dating event</a>, and heard that <a href="https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=270293426434770&set=a.270293423101437.64936.223782044419242&type=1&relevant_count=1">they serve Pork Ribs</a> at their 30$ Open Wine BBQ, I decided to give The Mansion a try on a Saturday night.</p>\n<p>Before calling to book, I checked out their <a href="https://www.facebook.com/themansionbeirut">Facebook page</a> for pictures and I honestly couldn’t figure out how the places looks like or how big it is. It didn’t make a big difference to me as I had heard it’s a cool place but I think they should add some clear pictures on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/themansionbeirut">The Mansion’s Facebook page</a>.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_235505-425x318.jpg" alt="20130223_235505" width="425" height="318"></p>\n<p>The Mansion is located in the middle of Gemmayze on Mar Antonios Street. It’s an old renovated house situated in an isolated area from the vibrant Gouraud street. Once you go in, there’s a large room with a bar on the left, high tables and chairs, cool chandeliers dangling from the roof and Botero paintings on the wall. There are other rooms more suited for relaxing and dining but you will be missing out on a lot of fun.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_235443-425x318.jpg" alt="20130223_235443" width="425" height="318"><br><em>Fat Monalisa</em></p>\n<p>Even though we got there early, the place was already half full but tables were comfortably distanced from each other and from the bar. Once we sat down, we were offered Champagne glasses for some reason. I thought it was a welcome drink or something but it turned out to be “Champagne Saturday” where everyone gets Champagne every time the bell rings.  </p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_220458-425x318.jpg" alt="20130223_220458" width="425" height="318"></p>\n<p>We ordered drinks and Nachos first, then The Mansion burger, a Mozzarella sandwich and a Breast N Cheese platter as main dishes. Everything tasted great and the service was impeccable. I don’t want to be exaggerating here but the girl (Rachel) in charge of our table was just great and made the whole experience even better. She’d check on us every 5-10 minutes to make sure our drinks are as requested or if we needed a refill, whether our food is delivered on time, or if we needed anything at all. I will suggest to the Mansion people that they name her employee of the month and add a funny painting of her similar to the ones they have displayed.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_222430-425x318.jpg" alt="20130223_222430" width="425" height="318"></p>\n<p>Moving on to the music, the DJ created a nice ambiance, far from trance and cheap commercial songs, and included some awesome songs from the 90s like Scatman or Cotton Eyed Joe. There weren’t a lot of people dancing when we left (Around 12:30) but the place was packed and everybody seemed to be having a good time. More importantly, no one was smoking inside. </p>\n<p>Price-wise, the bill was reasonable and we ended up paying around 40$ per person.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130223_235540-425x318.jpg" alt="20130223_235540" width="425" height="318"></p>\n<p>To sum it up, I had a great time at The Mansion and I will be visiting back soon to try the Pork Ribs. </p>\n'),
(131, 'http://blogbaladi.com/driving-school-in-jounieh/', 'Driving School in Jounieh', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130303_091232-425x282.jpg', '[High-Res]\nAs you can see, getting a driving license is serious business in Lebanon.', 'blogbaladi', 1362465600, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130303_091232-425x282.jpg" alt="20130303_091232" width="425" height="282"> [<a href="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130303_091232.jpg">High-Res</a>]</p>\n<p>As you can see, getting a driving license is serious business in Lebanon.</p>\n'),
(132, 'http://confettiblues.wordpress.com/2013/03/05/lets-sugar-shack-it/', 'Let’s Sugar Shack It!', 'http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre00.jpg?w=560&h=370', 'What do you do with the following ingredients: two cars, 7 friends, -5 C, a Sunday, Quebec?\nYou go to a sugar shack!\nSug...', 'confettiblues', 1362462480, '\n<p>What do you do with the following ingredients: two cars, 7 friends, -5 C, a Sunday, Quebec?</p>\n<p>You go to a <a title="Sugar House" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sugar_house">sugar shack</a>!</p>\n<p>Sugar shacks, or sugar houses, (<em>cabanes a sucre</em> in French) are very popular in Eastern Canada and between March and April is the season for what they have to offer. They are cabins that were established to make maple syrup. Sugar shacks now offer a meal in the cabin where most of the food is made with maple syrup and some even have a chimney and live music. In Quebec, it is quite popular during the months of March and April to go to a <em>cabane a sucre </em>to have a typical meal from the region and then have <em>tire d’erable</em> on the snow, which is maple syrup on the snow that solidifies into a caramel-like texture and then scooped by you with a wooden Popsicle stick! Simple, silly but fun!</p>\n<p>Needless to say, it turned out to be a cool Sunday. Here are a few photos.</p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre00.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre00" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre00.jpg?w=560&h=370" width="560" height="370"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre01.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre01" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre01.jpg?w=560&h=370" width="560" height="370"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre02.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre02" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre02.jpg?w=560&h=333" width="560" height="333"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre03.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre03" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre03.jpg?w=560&h=366" width="560" height="366"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre04.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre04" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre04.jpg?w=560&h=341" width="560" height="341"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre05.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre05" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre05.jpg?w=560&h=370" width="560" height="370"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre06.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre06" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre06.jpg?w=560&h=372" width="560" height="372"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre07.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre07" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre07.jpg?w=560&h=397" width="560" height="397"></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre08.jpg"><img alt="cabane-a-sucre08" src="http://confettiblues.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/cabane-a-sucre08.jpg?w=560&h=370" width="560" height="370"></a></p>\n<br> Tagged: <a href="http://confettiblues.wordpress.com/tag/canada/">canada</a>, <a href="http://confettiblues.wordpress.com/tag/personal/">personal</a>, <a href="http://confettiblues.wordpress.com/tag/photography/">photography</a> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/confettiblues.wordpress.com/2976/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/confettiblues.wordpress.com/2976/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=confettiblues.wordpress.com&blog=10776410&post=2976&subd=confettiblues&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n'),
(133, 'http://www.thedscoop.com/post/44558025530', 'Viktor & Rolf Get Their Mojo Back!', 'http://media.tumblr.com/71b61bc1c8d53c9e91f6481f50e359df/tumblr_inline_mj5jpqbcVM1qz4rgp.jpg', 'Viktor & Rolf have always been one of my favorite designers. So creative and innovative, they always had a twist to thei...', 'thedscoop', 1362427740, '\n<p>Viktor & Rolf have always been one of my favorite designers. So creative and innovative, they always had a twist to their collection. 2 seasons ago, I  felt like someone else had designed the collection on their behalf because of how bad and unlikely of them it was. Last season was better and this FW13 season is way better. This is a collection worth looking at and its very wearable. Their signature bow is bigger is visible and it moves around from one look to another, changing and transforming. I’m glad to see Viktor & Rold have got their mojo back!</p>\n<p><img src="http://media.tumblr.com/71b61bc1c8d53c9e91f6481f50e359df/tumblr_inline_mj5jpqbcVM1qz4rgp.jpg"></p>\n'),
(134, 'http://www.thedscoop.com/post/44556969691', 'Givenchy FW13, I Love You!', 'http://media.tumblr.com/a3fc9694a2e1bb6ac46b9bab6ff017c7/tumblr_inline_mj5ippMrw41qz4rgp.jpg', 'Would everyone please stand up and clap for Riccardo Tisci as he takes a bow, please? Thank you! I must admit I wasn’t...', 'thedscoop', 1362426780, '\n<p>Would everyone please stand up and clap for Riccardo Tisci as he takes a bow, please? Thank you! I must admit I wasn’t expecting the FW13 Givenchy show to be as eccentric as it really was. I love it! I love the pop-colored pixie cuts, I love the maxi sheer skirts, I love the comfy sweaters, I love the mix of tartan with winter florals, and most of all, I love those peplum-belt-things.  </p>\n<p>This style below is to die for. Comfy sweaters over sheer skirts- thats comfort-meets-sexy for ya! </p>\n<p><img src="http://media.tumblr.com/a3fc9694a2e1bb6ac46b9bab6ff017c7/tumblr_inline_mj5ippMrw41qz4rgp.jpg"></p>\n<p>I’m not quite sure what exactly this peplum-belt-thing is, but I can tell it comes in handy for those who want to cover up a belly. It’s definitely classified as an accessory and sold separately. I can imagine it would look interesting over a pencil skirt, too! Let’s wait and see till it hits net-a-porter! </p>\n<p><img src="http://media.tumblr.com/bab92b057299d3b5f3d267e014f74d7f/tumblr_inline_mj5iyuj3UK1qz4rgp.jpg"></p>\n\n<p></p>\n'),
(135, 'http://brofessionalreview.com/2013/03/04/trident-and-the-fun-absurd/', 'Trident and the fun absurd!', 'http://brofessionalreview.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/trident.jpg?w=545&h=201', 'BRecap: Trident and the fun absurd!\nBy Admin I: So i have to admit my secret crush on absurd advertising!! It’s just ...', 'brofessionalreview', 1362424680, '\n<span><iframe width="545" height="337" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/3CElBZMSRzw?version=3&rel=1&fs=1&showsearch=0&showinfo=1&iv_load_policy=1&wmode=transparent" frameborder="0"></iframe></span>\n<p><a href="http://brofessionalreview.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/trident.jpg"><img alt="trident" src="http://brofessionalreview.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/trident.jpg?w=545&h=201" width="545" height="201"></a></p>\n<p><strong>BRecap: Trident and the fun absurd!</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong>By Admin I:</strong></em><strong> </strong>So i have to admit my secret crush on absurd advertising!! It’s just super interesting when advertising stops deep-throating us with products to say the least, and just reaches out for fun, for the absolute non sense, that it starts to make sense!</p>\n<p>Trident campaigns have always been up to the level, creative and fun (See?! We have nothing against multinationals). It’s indeed a fun product that unleashes potentially playful ideas, where the team can experiment to an extent of sticking any random absurdity and it’ll work like magic!</p>\n<p>‘See what unfolds’ is an international approach taken by the brand, that kind of unified local/regional trident campaigns when it comes to look and feel. So the art direction is internationally set, a mix between real footage and animated illustrations, taken a step further by an outdoor beautifully executed concept: a bathtub race! The campaign stress on the unexpected feel that trident can give, and how out of the box the product can be.</p>\n<p>It’s a spot on adaptation of the international concept, though it might have been pushed way more if shot at a regular Beiruti area, a busy pop scene, that’s a bit less ‘tantes sursock’/beautiful neighborhoods!</p>\n<p>Cheers!</p>\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/brofessionalreview.wordpress.com/2515/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/brofessionalreview.wordpress.com/2515/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=brofessionalreview.com&blog=28964988&post=2515&subd=brofessionalreview&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n'),
(136, 'http://blog.octavianasr.com/2013/03/ramallah-is-palestine.html', 'Ramallah Is Palestine', '', 'No other city says Palestine to me more than Ramallah. At the Kalandia checkpoint, a large Israeli sign warns visitors t...', 'octavianasr', 1362422280, 'No other city says Palestine to me more than Ramallah. At the Kalandia checkpoint, a large Israeli sign warns visitors they are about to enter Palestinian territories and that as such their safety and security are under threat. The obvious separation wall Israel has erected is an eyesore that immediately sets a mood of desperation and isolation. The huge cement wall which Israel calls “security'),
(137, 'http://blogbaladi.com/carlos-slim-helu-still-worlds-richest-man/', 'Carlos Slim Helu still world’s richest man', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/carlos-slim-helu-6-425x212.jpg', 'Carlos Slim Helu is the world’s richest man for the fourth year in a row. He clocks in at $4 billion more than a year ...', 'blogbaladi', 1362420300, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/carlos-slim-helu-6-425x212.jpg" alt="carlos-slim-helu-6" width="425" height="212"></p>\n<p>Carlos Slim Helu is the world’s richest man for the fourth year in a row. He clocks in at $4 billion more than a year ago, thanks to surging stock prices at his financial arm, Grupo Financiero Inbursa, and at his Grupo Carso industrial and retail giant. [<a href="http://www.forbes.com/billionaires/?utm_campaign=forbestwittersf&utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social">Link</a>]</p>\n<p>The first Arab Billionaire is <a href="http://www.forbes.com/profile/prince-alwaleed-bin-talal-alsaud/">Prince Al Waleed Bin Talal</a> with $20 billion, followed by <a href="http://www.forbes.com/profile/mohammed-al-amoudi/">Mohammad Al Amoudi</a> with $13.5 billion. Both are from Saudi Arabia.</p>\n<p>As far as Lebanese billionaires are concerned, Prime Minister <a href="http://www.forbes.com/profile/najib-mikati/">Najib Mikati</a> <a href="http://blogbaladi.com/prime-minister-najib-mikati-tops-lebanons-billionaires/">tops the list for the second year in a row</a> with $3.5 billion dollars followed by his brother Taha Mikati with the same amount. The richest of the Hariris is <a href="http://www.forbes.com/profile/bahaa-hariri/">Bahaa</a> with $2.4 Billion then <a href="http://www.forbes.com/profile/saad-hariri/">ex-PM Saad Hariri</a> with $1.9 Billion dollars. </p>\n<p>You can check out the full list of billionaires as of 2013 [<a href="http://www.forbes.com/billionaires/?utm_campaign=forbestwittersf&utm_source=twitter&utm_medium=social">Here</a>].</p>\n'),
(138, 'http://blogbaladi.com/lebanese-state-security-buying-used-cars/', 'Lebanese State Security buying used cars', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130304_0727121-425x318.jpg', '[High-Res]\nI spotted this X-trail today with a Lebanese State Security plate number and the logo of a used cars dealersh...', 'blogbaladi', 1362413280, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130304_0727121-425x318.jpg" alt="20130304_072712" width="425" height="318"><br>\n[<a href="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130304_0727121.jpg">High-Res</a>]</p>\n<p>I spotted this X-trail today with a Lebanese State Security plate number and the logo of a used cars dealership in Lebanon on the back. The only explanation I could come up with is that the guy works in State Security and put the plate on his personal vehicle but I don’t know if this is legal or not.</p>\n<p>I thought I visit State Security’s website and email them about it but the <a href="http://www.state-security.gov.lb/">frontpage</a> wasn’t very encouraging.</p>\n'),
(139, 'http://blogbaladi.com/myriam-klink-lara-kay-and-nathalie-fadlallah-featured-on-france2s-telematin-show/', 'Myriam Klink, Lara Kay and Nathalie Fadlallah featured on France2′s TeleMatin show', '', 'I can’t believe she introduced them as being “very sexy stars, singers, and top models”. \nThank you Elie!', 'blogbaladi', 1362408660, '\n<p></p>\n<p>I can’t believe she introduced them as being “very sexy stars, singers, and top models”. </p>\n<p><em>Thank you Elie!</em></p>\n'),
(140, 'http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/27-minutes-of-beautiful-and-powerful-rap-from-arab-mcs/', '27 Minutes of Beautiful and Powerful Rap From Arab MCs', 'http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/1360315947-tumblrmhhbehrlpz1r4fn52o1400.jpg?w=610', 'If you’re a free-thinking, liberal and pragmatic Arab like me, you’re probably just as pissed off, hopeless and disg...', 'ginosblog', 1362406380, '\n<p></p>\n<p>If you’re a free-thinking, liberal and pragmatic Arab like me, you’re probably just as pissed off, hopeless and disgusted by what the Arab Spring has come to. We’ve deposed predictable tyrants to be replaced by volatile Islamist fundamentalists who are just as bad if not worse. Egypt is becoming an Islamic princedom with every passing day, Tunisian free-thinkers are being poached off one by one, Libya is at the mercy of fundamentalist terrorist groups and Syria is being razed to the ground.</p>\n<p>Voices of the youth who made the revolutions are being drowned out by Ayman El Zawahiri and Mohammad Morsi. My beloved Lebanon is being torn up to shreds between the rotting carcass of corruption, oppression and religious fundamentalism that is 14 and 8 March. We kicked out Bashar to get successors which are just as bad with their tinted windows and corruption. Our uneducated, radicalized youth members are being recruited to fight others and each other for Sunni extremists and Shiite Hezbollah in a war in Syria that isn’t ours.</p>\n<p>I can go on for volumes about how disappointed and disgusted I and many others like me are, but I am not as eloquent and powerful in my writing as these MCs with the sick verses they’re dropping to equally awesome beats. From Egypt’s Morsi, to Bilad Ash-Sham’s plight and Lebanon’s 14-8 delimma. Even the Gulf gets it’s fair share of verses. I really, really advise you to give the soundcloud I’ve embedded above a listen. It energized me and revitalized my desire for a new Arab world, ours, far from religion and corruption and tyrants, and close to the people, freedoms, equality and rights we all want.</p>\n<p>Khat Thaleth is awesome, and fair. They’re not anti-Isareli aggression <em>or </em>Arab hypocrisy and corruption, but against both and for <em>us. </em>For the first time ever maybe, I actually feel with other Arabs and have faith that there are many like me, it’s not all dirty beards and shaven mustaches, black burkas and no women’s rights, but real people, awesome people, who deserve the best.</p>\n<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/1360315947-tumblrmhhbehrlpz1r4fn52o1400.jpg"><img alt="1360315947-tumblrmhhbehRLpz1r4fn52o1400" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/1360315947-tumblrmhhbehrlpz1r4fn52o1400.jpg?w=610"></a>Their <a href="https://www.facebook.com/events/316843368435810/330174983769315/?ref=notif&notif_t=plan_mall_activity">EP was launched in Beirut</a> on February 8, which makes me proud of our little piece of Hell, Lebanon.</p>\n<p>Also, Lebanese folks might enjoy Track 6</p>\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12374/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12374/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=ginosblog.com&blog=11198665&post=12374&subd=ginoraidy&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n'),
(141, 'http://smileyface80.wordpress.com/2013/03/04/daily-prompt-twenty-five/', 'Daily Prompt: Twenty Five', 'http://smileyface80.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/2260519714_3b48a2c135_b.jpg?w=560&h=833', 'blue clouds by: alexindigo\n\nThe challenge for Today is to not use a specific letter in this post for The Daily Post Blog...', 'smileyface80', 1362405960, '\n<div>\n<a href="http://smileyface80.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/2260519714_3b48a2c135_b.jpg"><img alt="blue clouds by: alexindigo" src="http://smileyface80.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/2260519714_3b48a2c135_b.jpg?w=560&h=833" width="560" height="833"></a><p>blue clouds by: <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/alexindigo/2260519714/sizes/l/in/photostream/">alexindigo</a></p>\n</div>\n<p>The challenge for Today is to not use a specific letter in this post for <a href="http://dailypost.wordpress.com/2013/03/04/daily-prompt-25/">The Daily Post Blog</a>. I guess its easy to write a post without a letter! At least we could be cautious in a way we never use that letter. What do you think? Guess that even we shouldn’t tell about!</p>\n<p>When I was checking what my fellow bloggers wrote about this challenge, I liked what was posted in <a href="http://nrhatch.wordpress.com/2012/08/24/ella-minnow-pea/">Spirit Lights in the Way</a> about what a post that she read, I checked also her biography and was inspired by her will to become a <a title="Freelancer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freelancer" rel="wikipedia">freelance writer</a> and she achieved it. Like me, I have a dream to be a writer, a novelist indeed, and I believe I will be someday. I’ve finished my first novel two years ago, editing it from time to time, so when publish time is on, the novel will be near to perfect, it should be!</p>\n<div><a title="Enhanced by Zemanta" href="http://www.zemanta.com/?px"><img alt="Enhanced by Zemanta" src="http://img.zemanta.com/zemified_h.png?x-id=bb0e7dd1-c305-41f9-bf45-1bf3efc2b40c"></a></div>\n<br>Filed under: <a href="http://smileyface80.wordpress.com/category/english-writings/daily-prompts/">Daily Prompts</a>  <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/smileyface80.wordpress.com/4999/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/smileyface80.wordpress.com/4999/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=smileyface80.wordpress.com&blog=9248528&post=4999&subd=smileyface80&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n'),
(142, 'http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/abc-verdun-lot-location/', 'ABC Verdun Lot Location', 'http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/nrm.jpeg?w=610', 'So, I wrote about ABC Verdun opening in 2017 last week. But, like you probably did, I was wondering where such a big pr...', 'ginosblog', 1362403320, '\n<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/nrm.jpeg"><img alt="nrm" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/nrm.jpeg?w=610"></a>So, I wrote about <a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/02/25/abc-verdun-opening-2017/">ABC Verdun opening in 2017</a> last week. But, like you probably did, I was wondering where such a big project would fit in the somewhat overcrowded part of Beirut. I mean, empty lots in Beirut are virtually nonexistent, we barely even have places to park or parks. My good friend <a href="https://twitter.com/sam_lb">@Sam_LB</a> who’s much more familiar with the area was kind enough to highlight for me the most probable location, which fits in with the trapezoid-ish shape of the rendered image on ABC’s website.</p>\n<p> The coordinates are 33.884186, 35.484767 if you wanna Google Map it and play around little.</p>\n<p>\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12371/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12371/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=ginosblog.com&blog=11198665&post=12371&subd=ginoraidy&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1"></p>\n');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`post_id`, `post_url`, `post_title`, `post_image`, `post_excerpt`, `blog_id`, `post_timestamp`, `post_content`) VALUES
(143, 'http://www.plus961.com/2013/03/2013-most-powerful-lebanese-women/', '2013 Most powerful Lebanese women', '', 'Arabian Business published their 2013 list of the top 100 powerful women in the Arab world, and 12 Lebanese women made i...', 'plus961', 1362403260, '\n<p><img alt="100+most+powerful+arab+women+of+2013" src="http://www.plus961.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/100+most+powerful+arab+women+of+2013-300x201.jpg" width="300" height="201"></p>\n<p>Arabian Business published their 2013 list of <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-491768.html">the top 100 powerful women in the Arab world</a>, and 12 Lebanese women made it to the list, with the most powerful one being Nayla Hayek (chairwoman of the Swatch Group) who came in the 8th position.</p>\n<p>Below are the Lebanese woman who made it to the list:</p>\n<p>8. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491185">Nayla Hayek<br></a>14. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491286">Leila El Solh</a><br>\n31. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491286">Fairouz</a><br>\n39. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491339">Nadine Labaki</a><br>\n41. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491342">Nancy Ajram</a><br>\n42. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491344">Elissa</a><br>\n46. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491348">Anissa Helou</a><br>\n49. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491348">Cyrine Abdelnour</a><br>\n56. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491364">Najwa Karam</a><br>\n66. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491386">Octavia Nasr</a><br>\n81. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491410">Mona Bawarshi</a><br>\n90. <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?view=profile&itemid=491423">Christine Sfeir</a></p>\n<p>Is it a bit weird to see people like Nancy Ajram and Elissa making it to the top 100 while there’s no mention of Haifa Wehbe? Anyway, you can check the full list <a href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2013-491497.html?">here</a>.</p>\n<p><em>Thank you <a href="http://twitter.com/ivysblog">Ivy</a></em></p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Plus961/~4/cq4uRIGkK0g" height="1" width="1">\n'),
(144, 'http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/bank-audi-atm-cash-and-cheque-deposits/', 'Bank Audi ATM Cash and Cheque Deposits', 'http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/20130302_171621-1.jpg?w=610&h=468', 'I know this isn’t exactly new and has been around for some 6 months, but I’m noticing very few people know this is p...', 'ginosblog', 1362402240, '\n<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/20130302_171621-1.jpg"><img alt="20130302_171621-1" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/20130302_171621-1.jpg?w=610&h=468" width="610" height="468"></a></p>\n<p>I know this isn’t exactly new and has been around for some 6 months, but I’m noticing very few people know this is possible in Lebanon now. If you’re a student or employee, chances are you never have time to get to the bank before 2:00PM and wait in line. Also, who the hell wants to wake up early and get to the bank before noon on Saturdays. Also, no offense to any bank employees, whom many of my close friends are, but I’d much rather get the job done myself at my own convenience and any time of day with everything clear on a good old computer screen.</p>\n<p>Just the other night, while on my way to Uruguay street, I stopped by the LED-Christmas-tree-like Bank Audi branch in Dbayeh and deposited some cash I didn’t want on me. It took less than 3 minutes and problem-free. Just put in your debit card, place the money all-at-once without any rubber band, envelope, or paper clip, with the US presidents facing you, and you’re all set. It asks you if the amount is right before confirming the deposit, and ta-da, you’re done.</p>\n<p>I loved it, and the less trips and line-waiting at the bank, the better. Also, I’d much rather do things myself and see everything on the screen instead of communicating verbally with everyone around. I mean, what if you’re sorta broke and don’t want the entire branch knowing how little (or if you’re lucky, how much) you’re depositing in your bank-secrecy-protected Lebanese account.</p>\n<p>Here are a few shots of the ATM I used. I hope all ATMs and banks become like this in the near future, and mobile banking becomes more ubiquitous and has more functions than it does today.</p>\n<p><strong>EDIT: </strong>One thing I forgot (and didn’t know) is that when you go to the branch to deposit, the “value date” or when the money becomes available is 4 days. When you deposit in the ATM, it’s just 1 day. So, even more reason why this is awesome which I didn’t even know about. (Thanks Najib!)</p>\n\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/bank-audi-atm-cash-and-cheque-deposits/20130302_170730-1/" title="20130302_170730-1"><img width="150" height="112" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/20130302_170730-1.jpg?w=150&h=112" alt="20130302_170730-1"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/bank-audi-atm-cash-and-cheque-deposits/20130302_170736-1/" title="20130302_170736-1"><img width="150" height="112" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/20130302_170736-1.jpg?w=150&h=112" alt="20130302_170736-1"></a>\n\n<p>\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12363/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12363/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=ginosblog.com&blog=11198665&post=12363&subd=ginoraidy&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1"></p>\n'),
(145, 'http://remarkz.wordpress.com/2013/03/04/the-framing-of-a-research-question/', 'The framing of a “research question”', '', 'I came across this paper written for a particular Middle East Policy Council. I have never seen a more awkwardly posed q...', 'remarkz', 1362401340, '\n<p><a href="http://remarkz.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/resources-for-the-media.png"><img alt="resources-for-the-media" src="http://remarkz.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/resources-for-the-media.png?w=150&h=108" width="150" height="108"></a>I came across <a href="http://www.mepc.org/journal/middle-east-policy-archives/hezbollahs-survival-resources-and-relationships">this paper written for</a> a particular Middle East Policy Council. I have never seen a more awkwardly posed question regarding Hizbullah’s political development:</p>\n<blockquote><p>Hezbollah’s evolution speaks to a larger question in the literature on nonstate actors, both in the Middle East and elsewhere: Why do some nonstate military groups <strong>survive attempts to uproot them</strong> <strong>from particular pieces of territory</strong> while others do not? And what lessons do organizations learn from earlier confrontations that enable them to better survive later ones?</p></blockquote>\n<p>So Palestinian organizations, have been “uprooted”, “commies” too, other Arabic or Islamic infestious protuberances all gone. Now Hizbullah. Why are there only failed attempts at uprooting that bad plant? I mean, they did come from outer space (like all the other predecessors) after all? What can Israel or the US, the indegeneous, do to fix this problem? They did try everything after all…</p>\n<p>If, “<a href="http://www.mepc.org/about-council">The Middle East Policy Council</a> is a nonprofit organization whose mission is to contribute to American understanding of the political, economic and cultural issues that affect U.S. interests in the Middle East”, then it’s quite understandable that finding that “rootedness” is a resilient attribute of the link between Hizbullah to its people can pose a big problem!</p>\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/remarkz.wordpress.com/4502/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/remarkz.wordpress.com/4502/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=remarkz.wordpress.com&blog=3584669&post=4502&subd=remarkz&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n'),
(146, 'http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/', 'Alcazar Review', 'http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/562232_439898372706351_874974814_n.jpg?w=610&h=406', 'After Alacazar’s re-opening this past weekend, I looked through the blog’s archives and realized I had never reviewe...', 'ginosblog', 1362400980, '\n<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/562232_439898372706351_874974814_n.jpg"><img alt="562232_439898372706351_874974814_n" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/562232_439898372706351_874974814_n.jpg?w=610&h=406" width="610" height="406"></a></p>\n<p>After Alacazar’s re-opening this past weekend, I looked through the blog’s archives and realized I had never reviewed it, even though it was probably the venue I was at most in Gemmayzeh. So, after it’s relaunch and an awesome Friday night there with Nour, Mari-Joe, Celina, Fida, Samer, Karim, Gaelle and Hashem I decided it’s time for this long-overdue review of perhaps my favorite Gemmayzeh venue.</p>\n<p>Alcazar is located on the St. Nicolas Stairs, famous for the continuous art galleries, installations and festivals that happen on this historic staircase that connects the vibrant Gouraud Street with the truly magical Sursock Street, home to some of Beirut’s most beautiful and well-preserved traditional mansions and palaces. Alcazar blended in with its environment perfectly, and more so now that they have their very own art space where you can feature your work for free.</p>\n<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n.jpg"><img alt="316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n.jpg?w=300&h=200" width="300" height="200"></a>Alcazar is a three-floor, refurbished traditional Lebanese house that incorporates beautiful Lebanese stone masonry with the more modern steel and concrete minimal design. The ground floor is where we spend most of our time, where there’s a bar that runs along on one side with a few high tables sandwiched between the bar and the DJ booth and an elevator shaft that leads up to the two other floors. This area has been left untouched (thankfully, cause I liked it) and the relaunch has instead revamped the outer terrace, which is much-needed now for smokers who aren’t lighting up indoors (thank you!) and step out to find a cool swing and patio furniture to have a chat where the music is less loud and smoke a cigarette before heading back in.</p>\n<p>The first floor is the art gallery, and within two weeks, the first showcase will be up and running. I’d really love to see one of you guys and gals put your photos, paintings, sculptures or any other piece of art there, so make sure you contact them and see what you need to do (it is free though, I asked twice). The roof terrace also remains a surprise, since it’s still wintery and not open yet. But, it’s a really chill section with comfortable couches and a much more laid-back, loungy feel to it than the ground floor. It’s perfect for drinks and a dinner as the sun is setting and I’d suggest continuing the rest of your night downstairs on the ground floor for some good, beautiful House music.</p>\n<p>The music is usually different shades of House and electronic music with talents like Ronin and Nesta, Fat Dutch and Diamond Setter being regulars there last summer. Residents after the relaunch include Diamond Setter, Lady Bug, Dansz, Trix and Justine Baer. Of course, there might be theme nights every now and then for all you people who aren’t as hardcore House lovers as I am, so you might wanna look into that =P</p>\n<p><strong>The Verdict</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Location and venue</strong>: Out-of-the-way, nice underground venue yet still in the heart of Gemmayzeh on the St. Nicolas Stairs<br><strong>Music:</strong> A variety of electronic music (house, nudisco, indie)<br><strong>Atmosphere:</strong> Chill, laidback and sophisticated<br><strong>Wheelchair accessible</strong>: No<br><strong>Staff</strong>: Friendly and courteous<br><strong>Smoking:</strong> Indoors, no (thankfully). But, plenty of outdoors spaces for smokers.<br><strong>Prices: </strong>9,000LBP beers and 12,000-15,000LBP cocktails<br><strong>Contact: </strong><a href="https://www.facebook.com/alcazarbeirut/info">FB Page</a></p>\n\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n/" title="316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n"><img width="150" height="100" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n.jpg?w=150&h=100" alt="316028_295656220463901_2123890160_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/308400_295656277130562_190543858_n/" title="308400_295656277130562_190543858_n"><img width="150" height="100" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/308400_295656277130562_190543858_n.jpg?w=150&h=100" alt="308400_295656277130562_190543858_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/422102_376738785688977_282636910_n/" title="422102_376738785688977_282636910_n"><img width="150" height="99" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/422102_376738785688977_282636910_n.jpg?w=150&h=99" alt="422102_376738785688977_282636910_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/408018_377614428934746_1888063314_n/" title="408018_377614428934746_1888063314_n"><img width="150" height="99" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/408018_377614428934746_1888063314_n.jpg?w=150&h=99" alt="408018_377614428934746_1888063314_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/429453_381682461861276_754436077_n/" title="429453_381682461861276_754436077_n"><img width="150" height="99" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/429453_381682461861276_754436077_n.jpg?w=150&h=99" alt="429453_381682461861276_754436077_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/395410_381682531861269_1876304206_n/" title="395410_381682531861269_1876304206_n"><img width="150" height="99" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/395410_381682531861269_1876304206_n.jpg?w=150&h=99" alt="395410_381682531861269_1876304206_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/62589_425780467451475_149258311_n/" title="62589_425780467451475_149258311_n"><img width="112" height="150" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/62589_425780467451475_149258311_n.jpg?w=112&h=150" alt="62589_425780467451475_149258311_n"></a>\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/04/alcazar-review/562232_439898372706351_874974814_n/" title="562232_439898372706351_874974814_n"><img width="150" height="99" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/562232_439898372706351_874974814_n.jpg?w=150&h=99" alt="562232_439898372706351_874974814_n"></a>\n\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12351/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/ginoraidy.wordpress.com/12351/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=ginosblog.com&blog=11198665&post=12351&subd=ginoraidy&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n'),
(147, 'http://blogbaladi.com/lebanese-actress-nadine-njeim-lending-her-voice-to-lara-croft/', 'Lebanese actress Nadine Njeim lending her voice to Lara Croft', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/Tomb-Raider-2013-Lara-Croft-Wallpaper-HD-for-Desktop-425x265.jpg', 'Source\nNadine Njeim was elected Miss Lebanon in 2007.\n\nWhile the actress Camilla Luddington is providing the English voi...', 'blogbaladi', 1362400980, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/Tomb-Raider-2013-Lara-Croft-Wallpaper-HD-for-Desktop-425x265.jpg" alt="Tomb-Raider-2013-Lara-Croft-Wallpaper-HD-for-Desktop" width="425" height="265"><br><em><a href="http://hdwallpaperdownloads.com/desktop/tomb-raider-2013-lara-croft-2">Source</a></em></p>\n<p>Nadine Njeim was elected Miss Lebanon in 2007.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>While the actress Camilla Luddington is providing the English voice-over, the game has also been localised, with the Lebanese actress and model Nadine Njeim stepping in to give an Arabic lilt to the character, a first for an action-adventure title. “They just took out the English and translated it, but we had to adapt it to the tie frame we have and the lip synching we have,” says Njeim. “It was hard work because we tend to elongate things. A one-syllable word in English takes about 10 minutes in Arabic!”</p>\n<p>Although she was named Miss Lebanon in 2007, Njeim admits it was a somewhat daunting task to take on Lara Croft. “It was kind of amazing to see yourself acting out a character who has a legacy in the international community, not to mention the fact you’re presenting a new version of her this time,” she says. “I was obsessed with the thought that millions of people are going to play this game, millions of people are going to hear my voice. What if I get it wrong?” [<a href="http://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/film/lara-croft-is-back-and-shes-speaking-arabic-in-new-tomb-raider">Source</a>] </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/nadine_njeim_miss_lebanon_07_1.jpg" alt="nadine_njeim_miss_lebanon_07_1" width="416" height="309"></p>\n<p><em>via <a href="http://www.jadaoun.com/blog/6005/nadine-njeim-lara-croft-arabic/">JadAoun</a></em></p>\n'),
(148, 'http://blogbaladi.com/cool-gift-idea/', 'Cool Gift Idea', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/75940_605751922785372_1597216594_n-356x500.jpg', 'Picture taken from PureNostalgia \nPureNostalgia compiled over 2000 pictures of Lebanon in the 60s and 70s and put them i...', 'blogbaladi', 1362400080, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/75940_605751922785372_1597216594_n-356x500.jpg" alt="75940_605751922785372_1597216594_n" width="356" height="500"><br><em>Picture taken from <a href="https://www.facebook.com/purenostalgia">PureNostalgia</a> </em></p>\n<p>PureNostalgia compiled over 2000 pictures of Lebanon in the 60s and 70s and put them in a book. I think the book would be a pretty cool gift for parents who lived in that golden era as it brings back a lot of nice memories.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/385935_604876616206236_531078518_n-425x248.jpg" alt="385935_604876616206236_531078518_n" width="425" height="248"><br><em>The Old Zaitunay Bay</em></p>\n'),
(149, 'http://blogbaladi.com/confused/', 'Confused', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130302_145825-425x192.jpg', 'I am not sure if I should be laughing at the car or that he’s still bragging about his BB Pin.\n [High-Res]', 'blogbaladi', 1362392040, '\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130302_145825-425x192.jpg" alt="20130302_145825" width="425" height="192"></p>\n<p>I am not sure if I should be laughing at the car or that he’s still bragging about his BB Pin.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130302_145912-425x240.jpg" alt="20130302_145912" width="425" height="240"> [<a href="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130302_145912.jpg">High-Res</a>]</p>\n'),
(150, 'http://www.larmoiredelana.com/?p=10098', 'Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013 – Paris Fashion Week', 'http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0254-1024x680.jpg', 'I don’t know if her name rings a bell but last year, I also covered Claudine Ivari’s show during FW12 Paris Fashion ...', 'larmoiredelana', 1362389520, '\n<p><span>I don’t know if her name rings a bell but last year, I also covered Claudine Ivari’s show during FW12 Paris Fashion Week. It was a great discovery for me because I love to get introduced to up-and-coming designers and brands on the verge of making it big in the industry. This year, Claudine exceeded my expectations when it came to the quality of the materials she used, the mood of the collection, and the cuts she chose. </span><br><span> The fashion show took place in her gorgeous Parisian showroom, with gold details on the walls and huge chandeliers. </span><br><span> Most of the looks were in black with a couple of red outfits, some metallic gold details and a white short dress closing the show. As for the fabrics used,there was such a wide variety with everything from leather, wool, lace, crepe georgette to chiffon and tulle. The collection celebrated the strong modern woman; sexy when she’s all suited for work and extremely elegant for a dinner date. The models had slicked back hair in a ponytail with dark red lipstick. Take a look for yourself:<br><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0233.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0233" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0233-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0233 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0352.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0352" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0352-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0352 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0320.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0320" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0320-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0320 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0328.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0328" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0328-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0328 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0306.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0306" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0306-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0306 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0291.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0291" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0291-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0291 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0254.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0254" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0254-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0254 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a></span></p>\n<div>\n<a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0380.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0380" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0380-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0380 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><p>my favorite look from this collection</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0389.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0389" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0389-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0389 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a><p>another favorite, love the details</p>\n</div>\n<p><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0413.jpg" rel="lightbox[10098]"><img title="DSC_0413" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0413-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0413 1024x680 Around the World: Claudine Ivari, FW2013   Paris Fashion Week" width="584" height="387"></a> <span> Last but not least, I would like to thank <a href="http://unelibanaiseaparis.com/">Samar Youssef</a>, blogger behind “Une Libanaise A Paris” for the invite! Had such a great time scrutinizing each and single look with you.</span><span><br>\nFashionably yours,<br>\nLana xx </span></p>\n<p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/share.php?u=http://www.larmoiredelana.com/?p=10098" title="Share on Facebook">Share on Facebook</a></p>\n'),
(151, 'http://beirutspring.com/blog/2013/03/04/minister-sehnaoui-responds-a-willful-pragmatic-approach/', 'Minister Sehnaoui Responds: “A Willful Pragmatic Approach”', 'http://beirutspring.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/w460.jpg', 'On February 27th I wrote a post entitled: “Who wants to change the world?”, in which I criticised Minster Nicolas Se...', 'beirutspring', 1362388260, '\n<p><em>On February 27th I wrote a post entitled: <a href="http://beirutspring.com/blog/2013/02/27/who-wants-to-reinvent-the-world/">“Who wants to change the world?”</a>, in which I criticised Minster Nicolas Sehnaoui’s competition for bloggers to change the world. Minister Sehnaoui made the effort to respond with a <a href="http://beirutspring.com/blog/2013/02/27/who-wants-to-reinvent-the-world/#comment-35068">comment</a>, which struck me as non-defensive and with a sincere effort at persuasion. To give a fair hearing to the Minister, I will republish his comment as its own post below.</em></p>\n<p><img alt="" src="http://beirutspring.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/w460.jpg"></p>\n<p>Thanks Mustapha for this useful reminder to Lebanese entrepreneurs that nothing comes without hard work, sustained effort and perseverance. Of course the competition didn’t hint to the contrary. It is just intended to steer creativity and imagination. They have a virtue in themselves. I will mention three that come to my mind.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>To remind us of the power of ideas. I will refer you to <a href="http://www.aub.edu.lb/news/2013/Pages/telecom-revive.aspx">my AUB speech</a> which had the objective of unleashing the power of our youth’s minds.</li>\n<li>To force us to think beyond our borders, our physical limitations because a small country like ours can be one of the main beneficiary of this new geography where any point in the world can be its center.</li>\n<li>It will help us regain much needed assurance and self-confidence because contrary to what you said I do believe Lebanese have strong points in which they are better than other people. I do think that some of their promoted strong points which helps them succeed abroad are in fact some of the ingredients that destroy the country here at home. Their sense of trade, their ability to adapt, etc. All traits that diminish their national identity and their willingness to build a strong state. But what I am sure of, and more so since I took the helm of the telecom sector, is that they have a unique talent for creativity. Look around and notice: the best cloth designers if the Middle east are Lebanese, the best jewelry designers, most of creative in ad agencies are Lebanese, first cooks, hairdressers etc.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>It could be a way of the universal balance to give us something positive out of the fact that it made us a crossroad of religions, sects, languages and invaders. Let’s not waste it. In the digital world, the digital village it could be a plus that can help us outshine others countries and we badly need this edge.</p>\n<p>The other thing worth mentioning is that making Lebanon a digital hub has this fantastic benefit that instead of exporting our people we will be giving our local brains a chance to work from Lebanon and sell their products and services to the whole planet from right here. Dermandar (6 million downloads) and Pou (25 million downloads) are good examples that it is possible. It’s the fastest way to reverse the vicious cycle of emigration (economie de la rente).</p>\n<p>Last, let me insist on the virtue of positive approach. I know it’s tough in a country like ours where things seem out of our control and where the disproportion of force between local will and international players seem impossible to beat because of a deeply divided political spectrum. It’s tough but it’s possible. Its more than possible it is necessary or else why would we stay? Where would hope lie. We have to believe it’s possible and we have to try and make it work. That’s the positive attitude. That’s what drives me every day in the morning to get out of bed and face the infinite dangers and minefields of the political and administrative arena.</p>\n<p>For me it’s this or abandon our fate to the bad guys and accept that we cannot but move backwards. Although the country is at a halt in almost every aspect and the government have difficulty governing we leapfrogged in the telecommunication field. This is due to a resolute attitude, refusing to accept anything that would stop the necessary changes and the infrastructure improvements. Just remember that 2 years ago we use to wait half an hour to download 1Mega Bytes of emails. And there is much more to come. Of course it would be easier if all political parties and figures would accept to sideline telecommunications from the political struggle. It would also help if all citizen’s from all political or non-political sides would support the important infrastructure upgrades.</p>\n<p>I believe we should have a willful pragmatic approach. Yes the country is unbelievably tough and intricate. But what are we going to do about it? Whine until it gets better or put our hands in the works, set achievable milestones and achieve them and then start again.</p>\n<div>\n<a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?a=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?a=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:D7DqB2pKExk"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?i=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:D7DqB2pKExk" border="0"></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?a=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?i=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?a=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?i=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?a=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></a> <a href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?a=5VLVTVNzrS0:iCnnCKcCKIc:J3aVl1i_38o"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/beirutspring/fb_feed?d=J3aVl1i_38o" border="0"></a>\n</div>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/beirutspring/fb_feed/~4/5VLVTVNzrS0" height="1" width="1">\n'),
(152, 'http://bikaffe.wordpress.com/2013/03/04/%D8%A3%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A9-%D9%85%D9%88%D8%AB%D9%82%D8%A9-%D9%84%D8%B4%D9%81%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%B7%D9%81%D9%84-%D9%85%D9%86-%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3-%D9%86%D9%82%D8%B5-%D8%A7%D9%84/', 'أول حالة موثقة لشفاء طفل من فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية HIV', 'http://bikaffe.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/hiv1.jpg?w=540&h=543', 'شرح الدكتور بيرسود بالتفصيل حالة وجود طفل في الثانية من عمره في ول...', 'bikaffe', 1362387780, '<div>\n<p>شرح الدكتور بيرسود بالتفصيل حالة وجود طفل في الثانية من عمره في ولاية ميسيسيبي حامل لفيروس نقص المناعة البشرية منذ الولادة  خضع مباشرةً للعلاج بالمضاد للفيروسات الرجعية، في خلال18 شهرا لم يعد الطفل يمثل للعلاج بالمضادات الفيروسات القهقرية مع وفقد لمتابعة. عندما عاد إلى الرعاية في 23 شهرا، على الرغم من أنه كان قد إنتهى العلاج لمدة خمسة أشهر، وجد الطفل غير قابل للكشف الحمل الفيروسي. وأكد بطارية اختبارات حساسة للغاية عدم وجود فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية.</p>\n<p>وجاء التأكيد على علاج ممكن من منحة مؤسسة منحت للدكتور بيرسود  والدكتور كاثرين لوزريغا من جامعة ماساتشوستس في شهر سبتمبر 2012. المنحة يسمح الدكاترة. وبيرسود لوزريغا لإنشاء شراكة البحوث لاستكشاف وتوثيق ممكن علاج فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية للأطفال الحالات. ويشمل التعاون مع الباحثين الدكاترة. ستيفن سبيكتور وريتشمان دوغ في جامعة كاليفورنيا، سان دييغو، والدكتور فرانك ملدرلي في المعهد الوطني للسرطان، والدكتور تاي ووك تشون في المعهد الوطني للحساسية والأمراض المعدية.</p>\n<p>“طبيب الأطفال الطفل في ولاية ميسيسيبي [الدكتور هانا جي المتخصص في فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية للأطفال في جامعة ميسيسيبي] كان على بينة من العمل الذي كنا نقوم به، وأعملت فريقنا سريعاً بمجرد اطلاعه على حالة هذا المريض الشاب”، قال الدكتور روينا جونستون، نائب الرئيس وامفار مدير الأبحاث. “لأن التعاون كان بالفعل قائم، وتمكن الباحثين من الإنتقال إلى المريض  فورا وإجراء الاختبارات اللازمة لتحديد ما إذا كان هذا في واقع الأمر حالة الطفل في الشفاء.”</p>\n<p>وفقا للدكتور بيرسود، وأكدت الفحوص الشاملة مما لا يدع مجالا للشك أن كل من الأم والطفل كانوا حاملين لفيروس نقص المناعة البشرية عند ولادة الطفل، واليوم يمكن أن يتم الكشف عن أي علامات للعدوى بفيروس نقص المناعة البشرية في الطفل بالطرق الفعالة المتاحة.</p>\n<p>فقط حالة الأخرى موثقة لشفاء من فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية بالعلاج حتى الآن وهي تيموثي براون، ما يسمى ب “المريض برلين.” في عام 2006، بينما كان في علاج لفيروس نقص المناعة البشرية، تم تشخيص سرطان الدم مع السيد براون. وكان طبيبه قادر على علاج سرطان الدم له مع عملية زرع الخلايا الجذعية من الشخص الذي ولد مع طفرة جينية تسبب الحصانة للإصابة بفيروس نقص المناعة البشرية. بعد عملية الزرع، وكان السيد براون قادر على وقف فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية العلاج من دون عودة المرض له.</p>\n<p>هذه الحالة الجديدة يشير إلى إمكانية محيرة التي يمكن الشفاء التام من مجموعات مختلفة من المتعايشين مع فيروس الأيدز بطرق مختلفة. بينما قضية السيد براون كان نتيجة لسلسلة معقدة وعالية المخاطر، ومكلفة من الإجراءات، هذه الحالة الجديدة يبدو انها كانت نتيجة مباشرة لدورة غير مكلفة نسبيا من العلاج المضاد للفيروسات الرجعية.<br>\n“وبالنظر إلى أن هذا العلاج يبدو أنه قد تم تحقيق من قبل العلاج المضاد للفيروسات الرجعية وحدها”، قال الدكتور جونستون، “من الضروري أيضا أن نتعلم المزيد عن نظام حديث الولادة مناعة، وكيف يختلف عن لالكبار، والعوامل التي جعلت من الممكن لل ليمكن علاجه الطفل. “</p>\n<p>حالة ميسيسيبي تؤكد أيضا على أهمية تحديد النساء المصابات بالفيروس الحوامل، وتوسيع فرص الحصول على نظم العلاج يمكن أن يمنع من الأم إلى طفلها، وعلى الفور وضع الرضع على العلاج المضاد للفيروسات في حال ولادتهم مصابين بالفيروس.<br>\n“نحن فخورون لعبت دورا قياديا في تحقيق هذا أولا علاج فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية للأطفال للضوء”، وقال الرئيس التنفيذي لشركة امفار كيفن روبرت فروست. “وهذه القضية هي بمثابة تذكير مروع أن علاج لفيروس نقص المناعة البشرية يمكن أن يأتي بطرق لم نتنبأ بها، ونحن نأمل أن يكون هذا هو الأول من العديد من الأطفال الشفاء من فيروس نقص المناعة البشرية في الأشهر والسنوات القادمة.”</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.facebook.com/BiKaffe">مدونه بكفي على الفيسبوك</a></p>\n<p>المرجع : <a href="http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2013/03/130303172640.htm">المقال الرئيسي من مجلة علوم </a></p>\n<p dir="rtl"><a href="http://bikaffe.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/hiv1.jpg"><img alt="hiv" src="http://bikaffe.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/hiv1.jpg?w=540&h=543" width="540" height="543"></a></p>\n<br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/bikaffe.wordpress.com/529/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/bikaffe.wordpress.com/529/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=bikaffe.wordpress.com&blog=23317314&post=529&subd=bikaffe&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n</div>'),
(153, 'http://www.plus961.com/2013/03/lebanese-stars-running-for-the-elections-make-it-to-france-2/', 'Lebanese stars running for the elections make it to France 2', '', 'Not sure if we can call Nathalie Fadlallah, Myriam Klink, and Lara Kay stars… But anyway, in all cases tjarrasna.\n\n\nTh...', 'plus961', 1362385500, '\n<p>Not sure if we can call Nathalie Fadlallah, Myriam Klink, and Lara Kay stars… But anyway, in all cases tjarrasna.</p>\n<p></p>\n<center></center>\n<p><em>Thank you Giorgio Tarraf</em></p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Plus961/~4/mH9mTQN281U" height="1" width="1">\n'),
(154, 'http://www.plus961.com/2013/03/kidnapping-is-the-new-profitable-business-in-lebanon/', 'Kidnapping is the new profitable business in Lebanon', '', 'Check out this interesting report in Al-Safir today about the recent kidnapping incidents that happened over the last ye...', 'plus961', 1362384660, '\n<p><img alt="mokdad clan" src="http://www.plus961.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/mokdad-clan-300x200.jpg" width="300" height="200"></p>\n<p>Check out <a href="http://www.assafir.com/article.aspx?EditionId=2401&ChannelId=57767&ArticleId=286">this interesting report</a> in Al-Safir today about the recent kidnapping incidents that happened over the last year in Lebanon. So far, the responsible groups for these kidnappings were able to collect more than $16 million out of 19 operations, moreover one gangster is even coordinating these operations from inside Roumieh Prison where he’s arrested!</p>\n<p>And it doesn’t seem like kidnapping for ransom is going to stop anytime soon, due to the fact that the kidnappers belong to well known large crime families in Bekaa, so arresting few members will not eventually put an end to the whole thing. In addition, these groups just seem to have a strong appetite for making big money.</p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Plus961/~4/qCW-vpOeTbk" height="1" width="1">\n'),
(155, 'http://www.jadaoun.com/blog/5998/royal-jordanian-syria-flight-beirut/', 'Royal Jordanian Avoids Syria; Flight to Beirut Now Takes 1:45', 'http://i2.wp.com/www.jadaoun.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/RJ-New-Flight-Path-to-Beirut.png?resize=617%2C448', 'Royal Jordanian has decided to avoid Syrian airspace altogether due to security concerns:\n\nJordan’s national carrier R...', 'jadaoun', 1362382680, '\n<p>Royal Jordanian has decided to <a title="Royal Jordanian stops flying over Syrian airspace " href="http://www.arabianbusiness.com/royal-jordanian-stops-flying-over-syrian-airspace-491765.html">avoid Syrian airspace altogether</a> due to security concerns:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Jordan’s national carrier Royal Jordanian has stopped flying over Syrian airspace for security reasons, the airline’s head said on Sunday.</p>\n<p>[...]</p>\n<p>The airline, a leading regional carrier, said the move would primarily affect Beirut, a major destination, with a route via Egyptian airspace and over the Mediterranean making a longer journey of its four daily flights.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Well to be precise, the new route takes you over Israel, through the Gaza Strip into Egyptian airspace over the Mediterranean as the plane swoops into Beirut. <a title="Royal Jordanian 401" href="http://ar.flightaware.com/live/flight/RJA401/history/20130304/0500Z/OJAI/OLBA">FlightAware provides the clear mapping of the new</a> (and longer) route:</p>\n<div>\n<a href="http://ar.flightaware.com/live/flight/RJA401/history/20130304/0500Z/OJAI/OLBA"><img alt="RJ New Flight to Beirut Over Israel, Gaza and Egypt" src="http://i2.wp.com/www.jadaoun.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/RJ-New-Flight-Path-to-Beirut.png?resize=617%2C448"></a><p>Royal Jordanian Stops Flying Over Syria – Beirut Flight Now Goes Through Israel/Gaza/Egypt</p>\n</div>\n<p>The previous path through Syria meant that a flight to Beirut from Amman aboard Royal Jordanian took 50 minutes. The new path adds about an hour to the flight. The <a title="Royal Jordanian (RJ) #408" href="http://ar.flightaware.com/live/flight/RJA408/history/20130303/2015Z/OLBA/OJAI">return flight</a> seems to go deeper into the Sinai Peninsula and towards the southern tip of Israel before rounding back up north towards Amman.</p>\n<h2>Update: Gulf Airlines Skip Syrian Airspace</h2>\n<p>Thanks to <a href="http://www.jadaoun.com/blog/5998/royal-jordanian-syria-flight-beirut/comment-page-1/#comment-7837">chahe’s comment below</a>, I’ve investigated the matter further and tt appears other Arab Gulf airlines also skip Syrian airspace including Saudi Arabian Airlines, Emirates and Qatar Airways. Qatar Airways seemed to have changed their route on February 27, having traveled the day before through Syria. Emirates changed its Beirut route on February 25 and it appears Saudi Arabian Airlines has been doing it for some time (at least since February 18). All these changes have added an hour to what usually is a 3-hour flight.</p>\n<p>Anyone know of any other airlines that have changed their flight paths to Beirut in order to avoid Syria?</p>\n'),
(156, 'http://inkontheside.com/2013/03/04/how-advertising-works/', 'How Advertising Works', 'http://inkontheside.com/comics-rss/2013-03-04-How%20Advertising%20works.jpg', 'I don’t want to sound all preachy here, but I’ve seriously found it SO annoying when boobs are used to advertise pro...', 'inkontheside', 1362381300, '\n<p><a href="http://inkontheside.com/2013/03/04/how-advertising-works/" title="How Advertising Works"><img src="http://inkontheside.com/comics-rss/2013-03-04-How%20Advertising%20works.jpg" alt="How Advertising Works" title="How Advertising Works"></a></p>I don’t want to sound all preachy here, but I’ve seriously found it SO annoying when boobs are used to advertise products that have absolutely nothing to do with them! Unless you’re selling bras, then stop using boobs, and start coming up with some CREATIVE advertising!  '),
(157, 'http://saghbini.wordpress.com/2013/03/04/%D9%85%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%86%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%A9/', 'التيارات اللاسلطويّة المختلفة', '', '* مع صعود المبادرات والفكر اللاسلطوي (الأنركي) في العالم العربي، ت', 'saghbini', 1362369840, '<div>* مع صعود المبادرات والفكر اللاسلطوي (الأنركي) في العالم العربي، تبرز الحاجة لتوضيح مختلف التيارات الفكرية المتواجدة على خريطة هذه المدرسة الثوريّة، خاصة أن اللاسلطوية هي أحد المنابع التي شكّلت الإلهام لمشروع البذور (مع وجود فوارق مهمّة قد نتحدّث عنها في مقالات مقبلة). الإعلام والناشطون، وحتى الأنركيون أنفسهم، يتعاطون مع اللاسلطوية كأنها تيار أيدولوجي واحد، [...]<img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=saghbini.wordpress.com&blog=4965678&post=2122&subd=saghbini&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">\n</div>'),
(158, 'http://majnouna-blog.blogspot.com/2013/03/quick-food-not-fast-food-banana-bake.html', 'Quick food, not fast food: Banana bake', 'http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-aDXr-MPasQg/UTJphrR-QWI/AAAAAAAAJHM/7il1Y_K1MH4/s1600/Banana-bake.jpg', '', 'majnouna-blog', 1362364200, '<div dir="ltr">\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-aDXr-MPasQg/UTJphrR-QWI/AAAAAAAAJHM/7il1Y_K1MH4/s1600/Banana-bake.jpg"><img border="0" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-aDXr-MPasQg/UTJphrR-QWI/AAAAAAAAJHM/7il1Y_K1MH4/s1600/Banana-bake.jpg"></a></div>\n<br>\n</div>'),
(159, 'http://blogbaladi.com/whats-happening-between-champville-and-sagesse/', 'What’s happening between Champville and Sagesse?', 'http://img.youtube.com/vi/WaRtj8a3EdA/0.jpg', 'Sagesse – Sporting 2002 finale fight: The recent fights we’ve re witnessing in Lebanese Basketball have been happeni...', 'blogbaladi', 1362353400, '\n<p><iframe width="420" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/WaRtj8a3EdA" frameborder="0"></iframe><br><em>Sagesse – Sporting 2002 finale fight: The recent fights we’ve re witnessing in Lebanese Basketball have been happening for years </em></p>\n<p>To be honest, I didn’t follow up closely what happened during the Champville and Sagesse game few days back but from what I’ve <a href="http://sportkello.com/basketball/basketball/basketball-lebanon/13530-2013-02-26-16-19-21">read</a>, Sagesse brought more fans that it was allowed to, a lot of rules got violated, the whole game was a total mess and should not have taken place. Both teams got penalized, including Champville’s Coach Ghassan Sarkis and as a result of this fight, Champville’s president resigned from the federation.</p>\n<p>I’ve repeated on several occasions the real cause behind these problems in the Lebanese Basketball League and obviously no one wants to listen but I have a question to ask here:</p>\n<p>- Who’s the genius that decided to limit the number of Sagesse players and fans combined to 38 in an away game? Are you seriously asking a team as popular as Sagesse to restrict its number of fans to 10 or 15? What sort of logic is that? </p>\n<blockquote><p>- سنداً لاحكام المادة 210 التي تجيز للجنة الادارية اتخاذ اي عقوبة تراها مناسبة ، حيث ان نادي الحكمة خالف تعاميم الاتحاد وتجاوز عدد جمهوره 400 شخص في المباراة المذكورة بالرغم من ان العدد المحدد هو 38 بما فيهم اللاعبين والجمهور مما خلق جواً من البلبلة والفوضى وخسّر أفضلية جمهور للنادي المضيف، قرّرت اللجنة الادارية توقيف جمهور نادي الحكمة في اول مباراتين على ارضه. </p></blockquote>\n');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`post_id`, `post_url`, `post_title`, `post_image`, `post_excerpt`, `blog_id`, `post_timestamp`, `post_content`) VALUES
(160, 'http://rationalrepublic.blogspot.com/2013/03/can-lebanese-politicians-ever-abide-by.html', 'Can the Lebanese Politicians Ever Abide by the Constitution?', 'https://encrypted-tbn1.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcT1dsWjZjwAwhN4tfoCaCiNA2nD5m9yZrn4ovucw5wL-mtEAqJGSw', 'It is\nproblematic when the leadership of March 14 never tires of asking the\ngovernment to resign. I happen to think that...', 'rationalrepublic', 1362352380, '\n<br><br><div>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div>\n<a href="https://encrypted-tbn1.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcT1dsWjZjwAwhN4tfoCaCiNA2nD5m9yZrn4ovucw5wL-mtEAqJGSw"><img border="0" src="https://encrypted-tbn1.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcT1dsWjZjwAwhN4tfoCaCiNA2nD5m9yZrn4ovucw5wL-mtEAqJGSw"></a>\n</div>\n<div>\n<span>It is\nproblematic when the leadership of March 14 never tires of asking the\ngovernment to resign. I happen to think that this has been a very ineffective\ncabinet and that the time for a change is way overdue. But one should not\nexpect a cabinet to resign only because the opposition says so during press\nconferences only. There is a legitimate parliamentary procedure to be followed\nif and when any of the 128 members of the Chamber wishes to call for vote of\nconfidence in the cabinet as a whole. March 14, unfortunately has chosen not to\nfollow that path but instead to use the press to release statements that are\nneither effective nor meaningful. </span>\n</div>\n<div>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div>\n<span>If Mr.\nSaniora wants us to really believe that he is the reasonable leader of a large\nbloc of representatives in the Chamber then the least he could do is challenge\nthe cabinet in a vote of confidence, even one that his group cannot win. It is\nthe nature of these challenges that will keep the cabinet as a whole and each\nof its individual members sensitive to the demands and needs of the others in\nthe state. The same logic, obviously, would demand nothing less than that by\nMr. Geagea and his Lebanese Forces if they are truly dissatisfied with the\npolicies and the programs of the present cabinet. As for Sa’ad Hariri, I am\nafraid that he has given up the right to either head a new cabinet or even lead\na major bloc. Someone should remind Mr. Hariri that he got his chance and his\nperformance was and still is way below par. It is time for him to recognize\nthat politics is not his forte neither is leadership.</span>\n</div>\n<div>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div>\n<span>None of the\nabove is to be interpreted as an endorsement of Mr. Mikati who had a chance to\nrepeat his previous performance as a PM but instead decided to play second\nfiddle to Michel Aoun, Hassan Nasrallah and to act at times as if he is working\nfor Damascus. </span>\n</div>\n<div>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div>\n<span>A democracy,\neven a shallow one, is expected to at least be able to implement the major\nconstitutional declarations as prescribed by law. This means that nothing,\nabsolutely nothing, can justify not holding elections at the date specified by\nlaw.<span>  </span>One of the most sacrosanct\nprinciples in the rule of law is to abide by the details of the law as\nprescribed. These major institutional decisions are not to be handled casually\nby changing them whenever one desires. Laws are to be respected and it is the\nduty of governments, to take the constitutional responsibility very seriously.\nUnfortunately very few, if any, in the present cadre of Lebanese politicians\nseems to be up to this major task.</span>\n</div>\n<div>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div>\n<span>The Chamber\nis clearly forbidden from electing to the Presidency an ex Chief of the Army\nbut yet that was exactly what they did without even questioning the\nunconstitutionality of their act. As if that is not enough, they have failed\nfor twenty years to elect a Senate and to deconfesionalize the Chamber as well\nas all positions in the government. Add to the above the fact that the central\ngovernment does not dare exercise its power in certain regions of the country\nnor over some groups. It is not only that they tolerate the challenge to the\ngovernment authority but they even encourage it through their inability to\ntreat all regions and all citizens as equal. <span> </span>The above are only the tip of the iceberg: This\ncabinet as well as its predecessors have failed to combat corruption that has\nbecome endemic, have neglected to construct a reliable electric grid in a self\ndescribed tourist state and have dared to introduce economic legislation and practices\nthat defy any and all teachings of any school of thought in the field. And\nfinally the cabinets for the past twenty years have acted as if the national\nsovereign debt challenge does not exist; they hope that the probability of a\npotential offshore gas find is going to resolve this issue. That is so\nirresponsible that it reminds me of the Greek tragedies whose plot builds up to\na level that is impossible to solve until a deus ex machina appears. (A\nheavenly solution</span><span><span>:-)</span></span><span>). </span>\n</div>\n<div>\n<br>\n</div>\n<div>\n<span>The Lebanese\npoliticians have had so many opportunities to prove their allegiance to the\ncountry, to democracy and to law and order. Unfortunately they have failed\npractically every single time. I hope that they hold elections on time without\nany resort to such gimmicks as extensions. If they fail this time then it might\nbe one time too many. </span>\n</div>\n'),
(161, 'http://www.larmoiredelana.com/?p=10211', 'Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013 – #PFW', 'http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0811-1024x680.jpg', 'I always liked Rabih Kayrouz work especially when it comes to how he greatly masters the use of fabrics.I admire the ver...', 'larmoiredelana', 1362936420, '\n<p>I always liked Rabih Kayrouz work especially when it comes to how he greatly masters the use of fabrics.I admire the very fine tailoring adding his signature to the piece, every time in a different way. Nevertheless, in my humble opinion, none of his previous work equals the flawlessness of his Fall Winter 2013 collection. It was simply incredible. I’m sure you’ve already seen the pictures I previously posted on L’Armoire De Lana’s social media accounts and you might also heard how good the feedback was in all the international press!<br>\nJust as always, it was a collection focused on very-well tailored pieces with everything looking just right from the pants to the coats to the structured dresses. I particularly loved the fur details and the leopard print that was done in just the right tone. There were also a lot of dresses and what I loved about them is how light and comfortable they looked, which is not something we usually see in a winter collection. My favorite part were the colors,namely the bleu gitane and the coral red which were just amaaaazing!!!!!!! It was also interesting how Rabih mixed a bleu gitane sweater with a flowy leopard print skirt. Last but not least, I’m definitely getting a pair of the collection’s shoes. Aren’t they so sexy? Plus, although they have an arched heel, the models seemed so comfortable walking in them.<br>\nYour thoughts on the collection?<br><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0719.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0719" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0719-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0719 1024x680 Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013   #PFW" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0725.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0725" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0725-e1362935636116-680x1024.jpg" alt="DSC 0725 e1362935636116 680x1024 Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013   #PFW" width="584" height="879"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0728.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0728" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0728-e1362935706330-680x1024.jpg" alt="DSC 0728 e1362935706330 680x1024 Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013   #PFW" width="584" height="879"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0731.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0731" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0731-e1362935748204-680x1024.jpg" alt="DSC 0731 e1362935748204 680x1024 Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013   #PFW" width="584" height="879"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0734.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0734" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0734-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0734 1024x680 Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013   #PFW" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0736.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0736" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0736-1024x680.jpg" alt="DSC 0736 1024x680 Around the World: Rabih Kayrouz Fall/Winter 2013   #PFW" width="584" height="387"></a><a href="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0740.jpg" rel="lightbox[10211]"><img title="DSC_0740" src="http://www.larmoiredelana.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/DSC_0740-e1362935880461-680x1024.jpg" alt="DSC 0740 e136293