(359, 'http://blogbaladi.com/im-reading-superman-is-an-arab-by-joumana-haddad/', 'I’m reading “Superman is an Arab” by Joumana Haddad', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130316_000037-425x318.jpg', 'I only became aware of Joumana Haddad in 2010 after the controversy her first book ‘I Killed Scheherazade: Confessions...', 'blogbaladi', 1363413120, '<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/20130316_000037-425x318.jpg" alt="20130316_000037" width="425" height="318"></p>\n<p>I only became aware of Joumana Haddad in 2010 after the controversy her first book ‘I Killed Scheherazade: Confessions of an Angry Arab Woman’ <em>(Which by the way got translated into 13 languages and was universally acclaimed)</em> caused in Lebanon, a book in which she challenges “prevalent notions of Arab womanhood and, in the process, shatters the centuries-old stereotype of Scheherazade, the virgin heroine of The Arabian Nights who won the king’s affections.” [<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1569768404/ref=pd_lpo_k2_dp_sr_2?pf_rd_p=1278548962&pf_rd_s=lpo-top-stripe-1&pf_rd_t=201&pf_rd_i=190890609X&pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&pf_rd_r=1CE3G9S3E9P5X021XJ48">Source</a>]</p>\n<p>I haven’t had time to read the book yet but I’ve been following up on her for some time and got her second book Superman is an Arab as a gift. For those of you who don’t know, Joumana works as a cultural editor of An Nahar and is a renowned Lebanese poet, translator, journalist and women rights activist. Joumana is a ferocious critic of sexism in Lebanon and the way women are perceived and she expresses her opinions in an unexpected, captivating and daring way. Her unique take on the state of women in Lebanon and the Arab world has earned her a lot of plaudit and rewards but also a good share of death threats.</p>\n<p>In “Superman is an Arab”, Haddad turns her attention to men, decrying the ‘Superman’ of the title, a man whose “muscles are just a facade for his insecurities”, who “confuses manhood with machismo, faith with fanaticism, ethics with stale tradition, love with possession and strength with despotism.” [<a href="http://www.executive-magazine.com/consumer-society/joumana-haddads-superman-is-an-arab-reviewed/5305">Executive-Magazine</a>]</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/JH-by-Giorgio-Pace-2008-425x359.jpg" alt="JH by Giorgio Pace- 2008" width="425" height="359"><br><em>Picture from <a href="http://www.jasadmag.com/en/editor.html">JasadMag</a>, a glossy quarterly magazine dedicated to the body founded and run by Joumana.</em></p>\n<p>The threats of murder, rape and acid attack are not scaring or slowing down Joumana, and her latest two articles are a clear proof of that. In case you missed them, [<a href="https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/commentaryanalysis/dear_allah_where_are_my_72_virgins">Dear Allah</a>] and [<a href="https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/jspot/what-women-do-not-want">What Women do not want</a>] are awesome reads. </p>\n<p>To be honest, I don’t know how she does it, but she’s more courageous than most women and men I know. I could go on and on talking about her but I think it’s enough that you read her articles to know what I’m talking about. She reminds me in a way of Gebran Tueni, a good friend of hers, who crossed all the “red” lines through his editorials and was one of the bravest, if not the bravest, newspaperman the Middle East has known. </p>\n<p>In an <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2010/aug/21/joumana-haddad-interview">interview</a> with the Guardian, Joumana Haddad said that “she lives in a country that hates her”. Well <a href="http://www.blogbaladi.com/">BlogBaladi</a> loves you and will do whatever it can to silence the haters.</p>\n<p>Here’s a small brief on Joumana’s biography and achievements [<a href="http://whoisshe.lau.edu.lb/expert-profile/joumana-haddad">Link</a>].</p>'),
(360, 'http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/2013/03/16/oblivion-only-does-them-a-favor/', 'Oblivion only does them a favor', '', 'Startled with the noises caused by my room-mate at 12:30 a.m., I wake up from a Friday afternoon nap to become a hostag...', 'lebaneseexpatriate', 1363423740, '<p>Startled with the noises caused by my room-mate at 12:30 a.m., I wake up from a Friday afternoon nap to become a hostage of insomnia as my “awaker” surrenders to sleep.</p>\n<p>As I try to soothe my sleepiness with some reading, I find myself drifting with my thoughts, as always, across the Atlantic ocean, through the straight of Gibraltar and over the Mediterranean to hit mainland and pay a visit to the land of cedars, or whatever may remain of them.</p>\n<p>With a reflective state of mind at such a late hour (at least after waking up from a 4-hour nap), I ask myself the question that many of you living abroad tend to ask: Why do I always go back for mental visits? Why can’t I just capitulate to my reality and accept the new country of residence as a my new identity? Why the ever-haunting dream of going back? Why? Why? Why not? …</p>\n<p>All these questions are not new. Such questions become daily bread, commuting travel companions and sometimes even a the root cause of insomnia. Such questions are not by choice, not a result of an investigative mind looking for answers. Questions like these  are more of a form of self-dialogue, posed in a manner to alleviate the burden on their bearer while at the same time attempting to understand the reasons for a behaviour deemed unreasonable or perhaps inexplicable.</p>\n<p>Quite often, this self dialogue becomes a form of insanity, where I find myself in an endless conversation with my “self”. In order to rid myself the agony, I pass those thoughts on to the veterans in the field; those who passed through this decades before me, those who truly understand what I am going through, as they lived this agony when they left their beloved Lebanon and settled in their new homeland. Those veterans, just like the veterans of war, any war, sympathize with my agony but at the same time ridicule it, as they see how naive and idealistic it is. They advise me against cultivating those thoughts and allowing them to flourish. “Soon enough, you will get used to it and it shall haunt you no more. Give it a few more years, and you will be move on. Look at us, we were in your shoes years ago and now we think of it no more. Time will help you move on.”</p>\n<p>I might be still a freshman in the world of immigration, a novice in the world of homesickness, but I can clearly see how time has only cast its inevitability on those veterans, without helping really move on. When you pay a visit to their homes, you can see the Cedar, Baalbeck and Phoenician souvenirs hanging on their walls. You can watch the pre-set Lebanese TV channels provided by their American cable providers. You can smell the aroma of Meza spilling out of their fridges. You can taste the Lebanese coffee they still offer their visitors as a form of courtesy and hospitality. You can hear snippets of homeland news between their conversations as they gather with fellow veterans. As a matter of fact, you do not have to visit their homes to see how attached they still are to their homeland, for despite a few decades gone by, they still drive like Lebanese, talk Lebanese and perhaps most crucial to their survival, congregate into the Lebanese groups they have formed and based their lives around. Eventually, in order for them to survive, they had to create their own version of what their innermost being longs for. They have built Lebanese churches, mosques and convention centres  They celebrate Lebanese holidays, visit Lebanese families frequently and engage in political discussions with their Lebanese friends over every social gatherings. They have even raised their kids to love Lebanon, and their kids long for their homeland despite simply inheriting it and its memories from their parents. The <em>time, </em>they refer to as cure, has indeed helped them, but not in moving on and forgetting, but in allowing them to replicate the home they left behind and build a knock-off version that entices the mind and provides for the soul.</p>\n<p>So why am I still attached to the notion of returning? And why do hundreds of thousands other Lebanese expatriates still dream of going back one day?</p>\n<p>A lot of it has to do with one’s identity, the attachment to one’s roots and childhood memories. But I also believe that on a deeper unconscious level, it is a form of rebellion, a form of resistance.</p>\n<p>Most of us, were in one way or another obliged to leave. The wide majority of Lebanese, felt inclined to board that plane after their lives became endangered, or their futures threatened. Certain conditions were imposed on a wide majority of Lebanese that pushed them to seek life somewhere else, somewhere that was supposed to be temporary, until things got better, which eventually, to this very day, never did. These conditions that fell upon us, were imposed by a handful of so-called “chiefs”, “top dogs”, “warlords”, referred to in Arabic knows as “<em>Zo’ama - زعماء”. </em>These figures, who I refuse to call leaders, are in fact the oppressors, the criminals who assaulted us and the judges who have passed upon us the verdict of separation from our homeland. Yes, some Lebanese might support one arbiter over the other, but the fact that they blame one signifies that they feel victims of the game itself, regardless of which player they hate the most.</p>\n<p>This sentiment of victimization, this undesirable action of having to leave is what causes Lebanese like myself to remain attached to the promise of returning one day for good, of ending the temporary detachment from homeland. This is our only form of resistance, of taking a stand against those who forced us out of our land.</p>\n<p>On the surface, we may embellish alienation with justification, hankering with reasoning and nostalgia with hope, but deep down, our betrayed unconscious souls realize that oblivion is only doing them a favor and  omission is nothing but surrender to the oppressor.</p>\n<p>It might sound as a cliché, but I have to quote John Lennon’s most famous statement:</p>\n<blockquote><p>You may say I’m a dreamer, but I am not the only one…</p></blockquote>\n<p>If dreaming is all we have to cling on to our shattered hopes, then together we shall dream. I may have succumbed to their tyranny for the time being, but I refuse to do them a favor by moving on and letting go.</p>\n<p>–</p>\n<p>adel</p>\n<p>To receive future posts, follow this blog on F<a href="https://www.facebook.com/LebaneseExpatriate">acebook</a>, or subscribe via email by clicking the <em>follow </em>button on the top right.</p>\n<br>Filed under: <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/category/lebanon/">Lebanon</a> Tagged: <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/gibraltar/">Gibraltar</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-abroad/">Lebanese abroad</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-civil-war-survivors/">lebanese civil war survivors</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-diaspora/">lebanese diaspora</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-expatriate-blog/">Lebanese Expatriate Blog</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-expatriates/">Lebanese Expatriates</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-immigrants/">Lebanese immigrants</a>, <a href="http://lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/tag/lebanese-in-usa/">lebanese in USA</a> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/1240/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com/1240/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=lebaneseexpatriate.wordpress.com&blog=31197967&post=1240&subd=lebaneseexpatriate&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">'),
(361, 'http://www.plus961.com/2013/03/al-joumhouria-reporting-11-year-old-news/', 'Al-Joumhouria reporting 11 year old news', '', 'We will probably earn yet another Guinness world record with Al-Joumhouria reporting about an 11 year old news!\nCheck th...', 'plus961', 1363426500, '<p><img alt="aljoumhouria" src="http://www.plus961.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/aljoumhouria.gif" width="171" height="67"></p>\n<p>We will probably earn yet another Guinness world record with Al-Joumhouria reporting about an 11 year old news!</p>\n<p>Check <a href="http://www.aljoumhouria.com/news/index/61236">this article</a> published on Al-Joumhouria website yesterday about a girl that was raped by 4 men in Pakistan, and then check <a href="http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/07/06/pakistan.rape/index.html">the original story</a> on CNN dated July 6th 2002. This is a first I think eh?</p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Plus961/~4/CPmwGLeaUp0" height="1" width="1">');
