(666, 'http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/26/the-new-mercedes-benz-a-class-sporty-hatchback-perfection/', 'The New Mercedes-Benz A-Class: Sporty Hatchback Perfection', 'http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/72361_10151339811852218_795708275_n.jpg?w=610&h=406', 'Friends of mine on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram would have noticed I had one hell of a couple of days in Dubai last w...', 'ginosblog', 1364309580, '<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/72361_10151339811852218_795708275_n.jpg"><img alt="72361_10151339811852218_795708275_n" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/72361_10151339811852218_795708275_n.jpg?w=610&h=406" width="610" height="406"></a></p>\n<p>Friends of mine on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram would have noticed I had one hell of a couple of days in Dubai last week with <a href="https://www.facebook.com/MercedesBenzME">Mercedes-Benz Middle East</a>. The guys at Mercedes-Benz knew I <em>love</em> hatchbacks and were kind enough to fly me to Dubai to try out the brand new, turbocharged, direct-injection, 2.0-liter, 4-cylinder, front wheel drive, 211hp, 350Nm, 0-100 in 6.6 seconds Mercedes-Benz A250.</p>\n<p>After flying in and getting settled into the Jumeirah Creekside Hotel, which apart from the luxurious rooms and glass-floor pool 8 floors above the lobby, comes with a blue rubber ducky you can have a bubble bath with, which I most definitely did. After unwinding and enjoying the beautiful weather after spending most of the year in the freezing North East, I got to meet all the other awesome tweeps and bloggers from different parts of the Arab World. Good music, good cocktails and an awesome view of the Dubai skyline followed. We hit the hay early, because our day started at 8:00AM the next day and it looked like the guys at MB had quite a day planned.</p>\n<p>After breakfast and a safety and security briefing, we got to see our cars. 7 gorgeous A250s of different colors and I got my favorite one: black. We immediately got in and drove to the Pavilion, right across the street from Burj Kahlifa. It was a nice move, because we had basically no time to figure out anything in the car before taking it on the highway and the famous Sheikh Zayed Street, yet, we all had a seamless drive highlighting how easy it is to drive.</p>\n<p>The first thing you’ll notice is that there is no gear box to your right. Shifting gears up and down is on the steering wheel, and even though it took some of the participants a bit of getting used to, I found it delightful having them there which I prefer to a traditional stick to shift the 6 gears up and down. On that note, the A250 comes with economy, sport and manual mode which you can change with a button on the dashboard.</p>\n<p>At The Pavilion, we were shown a screening about the A250 then got to enjoy a really cool photography exhibition and a Segway race in the shadow of Burj Khalifa! Next, we drove to the Dubai Festival City where the real fun began.</p>\n<p>A course was set up for us that included a speed run, to see how fast we could get to a 100kmh, next up was a wide turn that led to a slalom course which finally, gave way to my favorite part of the course: the drifting! Three hair-pin U-turns, and two rough chicanes that let us push the car’s handling to the very limit (as you can see in the photo on the top of that post!)</p>\n<p>I got to do the course 7 times, which allowed me to try the different modes, speeds and driving. I’ll confess, I might not be the  fastest driver you’ve ever seen, but I am damn good at drifting. The drifting experience in the A250 was a bit new to me, because there is no handbrake, but instead a lever under the steering wheel to the left. However, if you put the car on manual mode, and shift down a gear right before doing the hairpin U-turn and braking, you should have quite a glorious drift that you had <em>complete</em> control over. I was hitting the hairpin at well over 80-100kmh and the A250 never once veered off-course or was tough to handle. The steering wheel was extremely responsive and as soon as you level it up and hit the acceleration, the car corrects its course and you’re ready to speed up again for the next hairpin.</p>\n<p>The chicanes further proved the worthiness of this car’s agility and ease of handling, which had me turning the wheel in opposite directions in a fraction of a second. The A250 wheels with the awesome 5-poke 18″ rims stayed firmly planted on the asphalt and the cones were left untouched in the extremely tight narrowing I had to maneuver through. In other words, it made sharp and fast turns in the slalom and chicanes easy, and I guarantee it would make any noob look like a bonafide petrol-head.</p>\n<p>It might be a sporty hatchback, but does have the three-point sparkling star on it, so luxury and safety you’re used to in the S and C classes were packed into this compact, beautiful package. There’s a radar in the front of the car, which when you get too close to the car in front of you, alerts you, just in case you were texting too much or lost focus. It also parks itself, which I tried, and was surreal seeing the steering wheel turn by itself. Another cool, techie spec was the car’s computer measures some 30-something metrics in your driving, from your speed, handling, music volume, etc. and if the computer feels you’re too tired (or maybe too wasted) a coffee cup light activates on your dashboard and the A250 asks you to take a break, maybe have a cup of coffee before you continue driving, for your safety and the safety of others.</p>\n<p>Most importantly, the car is gorgeous, absolutely gorgeous. From the rims to the grill and the interior, it’s sexy and sporty and young. Honestly, I would have never dreamed of buying a Mercedes-Benz or even driving one. I always feel they’re either too business-manish or girly. This car though, is a beast, and a hatchback and sporty, yet, just as luxurious and prestigious as the rest of the Mercedes-Benz armada. Another thing that made me start thinking of maybe someday owning this car, is the price-tag: the pimped-out A250 I drove is just 37,000USD in the GCC, and around 45,000USD in Lebanon considering our higher taxes on car imports.</p>\n<p>With this car, Mercedes-Benz is obviously trying to appeal to the people it never did before: the young folks. When you see a young professional, driving a CL 500, come on, we all assume his/her dad/mom bought it for them as a gift. This car though, would be your <em>own</em> car, or could be with the price tag and attitude it comes with.</p>\n<p>All in all, I adored this car, wholeheartedly. It was a pleasure being one of the first people in the Middle East to drive one and if I ever move to a city other than New York, the A-Class A250 will be the top contender in my favorite car slot: the sporty hatchback.</p>\n<p>It’ll be available in Lebanon starting April 15th, 2013.</p>\n\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/2013/03/26/the-new-mercedes-benz-a-class-sporty-hatchback-perfection/602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n/" title="602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n"><img data-liked="0" data-reblogged="0" data-attachment-id="12745" data-orig-file="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n.jpg" data-orig-size="960,639" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta=''{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":""}'' data-image-title="602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n.jpg?w=610" width="150" height="99" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n.jpg?w=150&h=99" alt="602774_10151339813082218_624045085_n"></a>\n<a href="htt