(942, 'http://hishamad.wordpress.com/2013/04/03/i-3-falafel-original-falafel/', 'I', NULL, 'If you sometimes follow my tweets (like I’m a huge celebrity and you all read my tweets) I have expressed my love for ...', 'hishamad', 1365007140, 'If you sometimes follow my tweets (like I’m a huge celebrity and you all read my tweets) I have expressed my love for falafel. This simple delicious sandwich is an easy meal to grab on your way at any time … <a href="http://hishamad.wordpress.com/2013/04/03/i-3-falafel-original-falafel/">Continue reading <span>→</span></a><img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=hishamad.wordpress.com&blog=15703444&post=2169&subd=hishamad&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">'),
(943, 'http://blogbaladi.com/justice-ministrys-higher-consultative-committee-reasserts-the-legality-of-civil-marriage-in-lebanon/', 'Justice Ministry’s Higher Consultative Committee reasserts the legality of civil marriage in Lebanon', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/kholoud-succari-425x271.jpg', 'Picture Taken from NowLebanon\nNow we have to wait for Minister Charbel to make his move but unfortunately I think the ci...', 'blogbaladi', 1365070440, '<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/kholoud-succari-425x271.jpg" alt="kholoud-succari" width="425" height="271"><br><em>Picture Taken from <a href="https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/Civil-Marriage-Features/kholoud-and-nidal-are-expecting-the-first-civil-baby-in-lebanon">NowLebanon</a></em></p>\n<p>Now we have to wait for Minister Charbel to make his move but unfortunately I think the civil marriage issue got buried once again or at least is pending until elections take place.</p>\n<blockquote><p>The Higher Committee for Consultations at the Justice Ministry responded on Wednesday to inquiries submitted by the Interior Ministry on the legality of civil marriage in Lebanon. The committee reiterated its support for civil marriage in Lebanon. [<a href="http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/78116-justice-ministry-s-higher-consultative-committee-to-interior-ministry-civil-marriage-is-legal">Naharnet</a>] </p></blockquote>'),
(944, 'http://blogbaladi.com/eurosport-arabia/', 'Eurosport Arabia', 'http://blogbaladi.com/images/eurosport-arabia-425x188.png', 'I always read Eurosport online and recently decided to follow Eurosport Arabia on Facebook to check out their updates. T...', 'blogbaladi', 1365069780, '<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/eurosport-arabia-425x188.png" alt="eurosport arabia" width="425" height="188"></p>\n<p>I always read <a href="http://www.eurosport.com/">Eurosport online</a> and recently decided to follow <a href="https://www.facebook.com/EurosportArabia">Eurosport Arabia</a> on Facebook to check out their updates. They are fun to read but I was surprised to see that some of their articles have nothing to do with sports and discuss matters that shouldn’t be there. </p>\n<p>What does it matter if a player is Muslim or not? Who cares whether Muslim (or Christian or Jewish  or whatever) footballers should or should not have tattoos? or how Islam will benefit at the World Cup on a sports website? or the Arab-Israeli conflict? Focusing on religious stuff is so unlike Eurosport.</p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/eurosport2-425x216.png" alt="eurosport2" width="425" height="216"></p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/eurosport3.png" alt="eurosport3" width="401" height="369"></p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/eurosport4-390x500.png" alt="eurosport4" width="390" height="500"></p>\n<p><img src="http://blogbaladi.com/images/eurosport5.png" alt="eurosport5" width="403" height="472"></p>'),
(945, 'http://ginosblog.com/2013/04/04/12-gorgeous-examples-of-lebanese-architecture/', '12 Gorgeous Examples of Lebanese Architecture', 'http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/img_20130327_144325.jpg?w=610&h=610', 'In my brief stint in Beirut, I came across a lot of beautiful houses, most of which were now derelict and about to be ...', 'ginosblog', 1365069960, '<p><a href="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/img_20130327_144325.jpg"><img alt="IMG_20130327_144325" src="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/img_20130327_144325.jpg?w=610&h=610" width="610" height="610"></a>In my brief stint in Beirut, I came across a <em>lot </em>of beautiful houses, most of which were now derelict and about to be demolished. I don’t know why, but I find places like that especially charming and captivating. There’s something about the abandoned that draws my eye and interest.</p>\n<p>I hope you enjoy these photos, and hopefully, these houses might survive the onslaught of bulldozers and cement and maybe one day become useful again: homes, museums, libraries, art centers and maybe even a research lab?</p>\n<p>For more of the Old vs New series and cool shots from across the world, follow me on Instagram <a href="http://instagram.com/ginoraidy">@GinoRaidy</a></p>\n\n<a href="http://ginosblog.com/?attachment_id=12876" title="IMG_20130313_063931"><img data-liked="0" data-reblogged="0" data-attachment-id="12876" data-orig-file="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/img_20130313_063931.jpg" data-orig-size="1776,1776" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta=''{"aperture":"0","credit":"","camera":"","caption":"","created_timestamp":"0","copyright":"","focal_length":"0","iso":"0","shutter_speed":"0","title":""}'' data-image-title="IMG_20130313_063931" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/img_20130313_063931.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="http://ginoraidy.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/img_20130313_063931.jpg?w=610" wid